WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.200
I am the aforementioned Hunter, who is very lucky to work with Kelly Bodwin at Cal Poly

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:13.000
University down in San Luis Obispo.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:18.240
I teach a lot of statistical computing and data science type courses in lots of different

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:19.240
languages and stuff.

00:00:19.240 --> 00:00:23.320
And I feel like what's pretty much agreed on at this point, even though a lot of the

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:28.040
education surrounding data science is still in flux, is there's math, there's statistics,

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:32.119
there's computer science, and then there's some kind of domain application knowledge.

00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:35.740
That third, usually, element of the Venn diagram that you've probably all seen or heard of

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:36.880
or something like that.

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:41.759
But it's that third piece, the domain knowledge or application, that can vary so much in everybody's

00:00:41.759 --> 00:00:44.980
kind of implementation of data science education.

00:00:44.980 --> 00:00:49.799
But I would argue that these things should remain constant.

00:00:49.799 --> 00:00:53.840
So if we can all agree on the math, the statistics, the computer science, and those kinds of skills

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:00.320
with whatever language you may happen to see it in, and no matter what domain application

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:07.940
you see or experience or deliver to your students, these things need to be in all of it.

00:01:07.940 --> 00:01:11.760
You may have courses in data structures, you may have courses in regression models or machine

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:13.540
learning and stuff like that.

00:01:13.540 --> 00:01:20.279
But at least at Cal Poly, we don't have a course in version control or a course in reproducibility.

00:01:20.279 --> 00:01:24.400
But these are things that are inherent and important for all of these topics and all

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:25.400
of these courses.

00:01:25.400 --> 00:01:26.400
Students need to see these things.

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:31.320
These need to be harped on and emphasized, I think, in any data science education.

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:37.900
So besides positing that these are kind of foundational, R and RStudio are really special

00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:42.959
tools for implementing and involving these topics, I think.

00:01:42.959 --> 00:01:45.739
So to start off, reproducibility.

00:01:45.739 --> 00:01:48.440
This is like the deadest horse, I feel like, of this conference.

00:01:48.440 --> 00:01:51.639
You guys have heard about reproducibility in lots and lots of talks already, so there's

00:01:51.639 --> 00:01:55.919
actually not too much for me to say here except what you already know, in one sense.

00:01:55.919 --> 00:02:00.080
So the idea, if you can't read the text, Shai is saying, what am I supposed to be looking

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:01.080
for?

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:04.120
If you're being passed code by somebody else or if I have students passing code around

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:09.000
or things like that, then that code should be kind of robust enough and built in such

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:16.279
a good way that it can be kind of run as is, that analyses, workflows, pipelines are reproducible.

00:02:16.279 --> 00:02:18.080
So you shouldn't have to really look for anything.

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:20.800
And if you are going to look for anything, you want to tweak anything, it should be kind

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:23.759
of parameterized well, built in a robust way.

00:02:23.759 --> 00:02:26.720
But again, you guys have already heard this a lot of times.

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:33.160
If you weren't at JJ's keynote, go check that out for how RStudio is epic at reproducibility

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:39.440
or Carl Howe's talk from yesterday on education where he also talked about how awesome RStudio

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:43.880
is for reproducibility.

00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:45.679
Communication should not be magic, right?

00:02:45.679 --> 00:02:50.639
It shouldn't be just a black box for how all the data science gets done, right?

00:02:50.639 --> 00:02:53.919
We're all delivering to somebody, it might be a teammate, it might be a supervisor, it

00:02:53.919 --> 00:02:57.320
might be people in all different kinds of positions or on different teams and things

00:02:57.320 --> 00:02:58.320
like that.

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:04.580
And the how of what we did and the why and all that kind of stuff shouldn't be magic.

00:03:04.580 --> 00:03:08.979
But this GIF's awesome, so I had to include that.

00:03:08.979 --> 00:03:13.559
And so communication has to be a huge part of whatever coursework our students are going

00:03:13.559 --> 00:03:14.559
through, right?

00:03:14.559 --> 00:03:16.839
And RMarkdown and Shiny are phenomenal at that.

00:03:16.839 --> 00:03:18.399
You guys have seen tons and tons of talks.

00:03:18.399 --> 00:03:21.960
I'm learning new things all the time about different ways that these can be used to that

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:23.199
end.

00:03:23.199 --> 00:03:26.919
So Gordon Shotwell's talk was really nice yesterday on technical debt, but everything

00:03:26.919 --> 00:03:32.479
you've seen so far on RMarkdown here is good for communication.

00:03:32.479 --> 00:03:33.779
Version control, right?

00:03:33.779 --> 00:03:37.160
There's all these different versions of possibly the same thing, right?

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:40.399
Code analysis and stuff like that going on.

00:03:40.399 --> 00:03:42.839
And you've got to track it, right?

00:03:42.839 --> 00:03:48.000
Along with reproducibility, we need resiliency in the data science pipeline.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.619
And so the Git integration in RStudio, again, is totally epic, right?

00:03:52.619 --> 00:03:55.880
So if you're not familiar with this, you probably all use version control of some sort, and

00:03:55.880 --> 00:03:59.119
you may use it outside of RStudio, but you can use it from within RStudio, so I would

00:03:59.119 --> 00:04:04.199
definitely recommend checking that out and getting your students hooked up to that.

00:04:04.199 --> 00:04:08.240
Practical application, you've probably heard this implemented in a lot of people's different

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:13.399
universities or programs, programs, programs, programs.

00:04:13.399 --> 00:04:14.399
There's a practicum, right?

00:04:14.399 --> 00:04:16.279
Or some client-based project or something like that.

00:04:16.279 --> 00:04:17.320
This is also critical.

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:20.880
We can equip students all we want in the classroom, but this football helmet's not really useful

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:21.880
in the classroom, right?

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:24.359
You can give them all the tools and stuff, but you've got to get them practice with it,

00:04:24.359 --> 00:04:26.519
like real practice with it.

00:04:26.519 --> 00:04:29.200
And so learn by doing, client-based projects are huge.

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:32.200
R projects are obviously a really nice tool for that.

00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:35.220
R packages and having students maybe build packages and stuff like that are all really

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:41.459
good ways to kind of get them into that mode of what they might be doing later on the job.

00:04:41.459 --> 00:04:43.019
And finally, data ethics.

00:04:43.019 --> 00:04:48.540
This often maybe gets swept to the side or isn't explicitly addressed, but everything

00:04:48.540 --> 00:04:53.019
and everybody involved in the data need to be cool with it, right?

00:04:53.019 --> 00:04:54.920
Need to be on the right side of it.

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:58.859
This has also been talked and touched on in a lot of different ways here at the conference,

00:04:58.859 --> 00:05:03.079
and so I won't say too much, except that everybody needs to be treated and considered well.

00:05:03.079 --> 00:05:06.000
So that is it.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Please reach out.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:08.839
I'm happy to discuss education with anybody and everybody, so.

00:05:08.839 --> 00:05:09.839
Thank you.

00:05:09.839 --> 00:05:09.839


